1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:26,324
So this is just an opportunity really to just revise the principles of our meditation, you know, why do we do it and how do we do it.

2
00:00:26,676 --> 00:00:32,423
And I'm aware that there are people in the hall that haven't heard anything about this all very little.

3
00:00:33,223 --> 00:00:39,832
And also that people have been at it longer than me, so try and get a balance just to what we say.

4
00:00:47,460 --> 00:00:51,164
The Buddha himself, remember, began

5
00:00:51,246 --> 00:00:56,371
in a position that we are, you know, searching for happiness.

6
00:00:56,813 --> 00:00:58,234
And that's basically what we're trying to do.

7
00:00:58,253 --> 00:01:01,537
We're trying to be happy, for heaven's sake.

8
00:01:03,600 --> 00:01:21,117
And at the time when he finally broke through what he called the delusion, the basic ignorance that we live under, he was able to point to three ways in which we can investigate

9
00:01:21,941 --> 00:01:48,641
our experience and to correct the way we are looking at things the way we're relating to things you could say that our basic problem is one of relationship he talked about them as the three characteristics of existence so in the meditation practice we did

10
00:01:48,722 --> 00:01:59,956
The first thing is to really begin to get close to this idea of impermanence and what that actually means in terms of a direct experience.

11
00:02:01,278 --> 00:02:07,805
So, it's not as though that comes as a great shock to anybody that things arise and pass away.

12
00:02:07,846 --> 00:02:12,891
It's not as though, generally speaking, people are not aware that the seasons do change.

13
00:02:13,973 --> 00:02:18,038
But it's really turning that inward towards ourselves

14
00:02:18,507 --> 00:02:44,110
and to recognize that we are in a process of change and that the change is not simply something that's changing shape like you might take a piece of clay turn it into a saucer screw it up and then turn it into a cup it's actually radical things are dying and passing away and the great exemplar of that of course is our own bodies

15
00:02:45,187 --> 00:02:49,353
Every cell is arising, dying and passing away.

16
00:02:49,393 --> 00:02:53,657
We don't experience that, at least I haven't.

17
00:02:53,938 --> 00:02:56,222
I haven't experienced the death of a cell.

18
00:02:58,805 --> 00:03:03,491
But I'm quite aware that in fact cells are arising and passing away.

19
00:03:03,510 --> 00:03:12,223
And it's that ability to really go into ourselves and see that all the experience that we're having

20
00:03:13,080 --> 00:03:38,262
is in this process of coming into being and then passing out and that the mind with its conceptual ability draws us into an idea of continuity so there is this feeling in me that I've always been me since the day I was born you know my body changes but not me

21
00:03:39,742 --> 00:03:41,125
I mean, my thoughts have changed.

22
00:03:41,205 --> 00:03:42,546
I don't think like a three-year-old.

23
00:03:43,288 --> 00:03:43,568
I think.

24
00:03:44,588 --> 00:03:45,069
Not anymore.

25
00:03:46,312 --> 00:03:47,272
But I haven't changed.

26
00:03:48,794 --> 00:03:52,860
I don't have the same emotions as a child, but I haven't changed.

27
00:03:54,682 --> 00:03:54,763
See?

28
00:03:54,782 --> 00:03:58,326
There's always this feeling that there's a me inside all this, which isn't changing.

29
00:03:58,426 --> 00:03:59,308
It's absolutely steady.

30
00:04:00,129 --> 00:04:01,991
And somehow I anchor myself to that.

31
00:04:03,454 --> 00:04:05,717
And when I actually investigate it,

32
00:04:07,300 --> 00:04:13,429
and I begin to describe what this me is, what do I end up experiencing?

33
00:04:16,694 --> 00:04:23,184
So I'm turning into myself, and I observe that everything I'm experiencing is passing away.

34
00:04:23,785 --> 00:04:26,129
But I still have this sense of me, the observer.

35
00:04:27,750 --> 00:04:35,382
Somehow I've retreated out of the body, out of the emotions, out of the mind, and I've found this other place within myself.

36
00:04:36,494 --> 00:05:00,004
that I experience as the feeler or the experiencer or the knower and it's very sometimes very strong that oh this is me I'm the one who knows now from that position we're quite privileged because we can at least abstract ourselves from these other identities that we've had so we've had the identity of the body

37
00:05:00,372 --> 00:05:23,646
now these days it's very difficult to go back to that very early childhood state where you are the body but we do occasionally sort of get that for instance when was the last time you trapped your finger in a door see for that one moment you are the body it's like it's a wonderful complete moment of pain there is only pain

38
00:05:25,177 --> 00:05:28,865
Then, of course, you shoot out of it and suddenly there's some body feeling the pain.

39
00:05:29,925 --> 00:05:31,569
There's an objectivity comes to it.

40
00:05:31,970 --> 00:05:40,264
But at least there we can sort of grasp what it is to be a self that is just the body, as a baby is supposed to be.

41
00:05:41,406 --> 00:05:42,528
I can't remember, you see.

42
00:05:43,302 --> 00:05:46,767
Then there's the emotional self, which is much easier to get lost into.

43
00:05:47,067 --> 00:05:48,810
You know, suddenly I am angry.

44
00:05:49,151 --> 00:05:50,233
There's no separation.

45
00:05:50,593 --> 00:05:53,098
I just blow it, you know, bang the doors and all that sort of stuff.

46
00:05:53,699 --> 00:05:57,225
Or I panic and I just become that fear.

47
00:05:57,745 --> 00:05:58,848
Or I'm depressed.

48
00:05:58,987 --> 00:06:04,456
I associate with, I identify with in a total way that this is me, right?

49
00:06:05,017 --> 00:06:07,442
Occasionally I'm happy, which is wonderful, see?

50
00:06:07,721 --> 00:06:09,444
And then I...

51
00:06:09,425 --> 00:06:15,033
And being happy, being joyful, you then of course get that sense of loss when it disappears.

52
00:06:15,574 --> 00:06:23,105
But there's this self which attaches itself to an emotion, which defines itself as I am happy.

53
00:06:23,485 --> 00:06:25,129
I and happiness are the same.

54
00:06:25,509 --> 00:06:26,531
I and anger are the same.

55
00:06:28,192 --> 00:06:35,904
But here in meditation what we discover is that there is anger, there is depression, there is happiness.

56
00:06:36,086 --> 00:06:37,848
Somehow I've detached from it.

57
00:06:38,370 --> 00:06:41,653
Now this word detachment, that's what you'll get in the literature.

58
00:06:43,036 --> 00:06:44,398
It gives it a certain coldness.

59
00:06:45,278 --> 00:06:54,129
Another word that you might find used is non-attachment, which gives it a sense of not just wanting to push away or a coldness to it.

60
00:06:54,471 --> 00:07:01,098
It's just there's a sense of separateness from the emotion that you're feeling.

61
00:07:05,483 --> 00:07:10,088
And then with thoughts, these are even more difficult as we discover in our meditation.

62
00:07:10,148 --> 00:07:12,050
Suddenly I'm thinking.

63
00:07:12,449 --> 00:07:15,033
There's no objectivity to it.

64
00:07:15,052 --> 00:07:17,074
I'm just lost in a dream sequence.

65
00:07:17,095 --> 00:07:19,757
I'm just lost in a whole flow of thoughts.

66
00:07:20,079 --> 00:07:25,384
And suddenly I come out of it, you see, by which time I can only note what has actually happened.

67
00:07:25,704 --> 00:07:29,067
I can't note it while it's happening because I'm lost in it.

68
00:07:29,788 --> 00:07:33,533
And in that moment I've become the intellectual self, the thinking self.

69
00:07:34,930 --> 00:07:39,255
So we're constantly moving from these definitions of a self.

70
00:07:40,336 --> 00:07:47,365
And in meditation, we're finding this other place where this observation post, which one writer happily called it.

71
00:07:50,670 --> 00:07:52,112
I'm trying to think of the name of the book now.

72
00:07:52,153 --> 00:07:53,053
It's Nyanaponika.

73
00:07:54,014 --> 00:07:55,276
Does somebody know it?

74
00:07:56,639 --> 00:07:57,480
Nyanaponika.

75
00:07:58,180 --> 00:07:59,942
The Heart of Buddhist Meditation.

76
00:07:59,963 --> 00:08:01,665
It still remains a classic, that book.

77
00:08:03,367 --> 00:08:04,548
And...

78
00:08:05,709 --> 00:08:27,634
we're finding this other place within ourselves from which we can observe these things and we're observing that they're arising and passing away but in so doing we've also found a space there's also a space between a sense of distance from what we're actually experiencing within ourselves, right?

79
00:08:27,951 --> 00:08:38,383
and that sense of space is the not-self not me, not mine so often you get this confusion in

80
00:08:39,409 --> 00:09:08,370
in the teaching where we think the Buddha is making some sort of metaphysical statement there is no self there is no body but when you look at his actual teaching in the scriptures it's just a way of beginning to realize what or who or whatever it is that we really are and we're doing it by pushing away by making an object of everything within us now as soon as something becomes an object it obviously can't be the subject

81
00:09:09,008 --> 00:09:10,350
I'm not pushing away.

82
00:09:10,409 --> 00:09:14,115
So when I look at my hand, I'm still attached to it.

83
00:09:15,255 --> 00:09:18,980
But that objectivity means that it can't be me.

84
00:09:19,020 --> 00:09:20,342
It can't be that which knows.

85
00:09:22,325 --> 00:09:30,576
And I'm taking that objectivity into myself so that when I feel an emotion, I'm feeling it, I'm looking at it, I'm experiencing it.

86
00:09:31,017 --> 00:09:33,159
And there's that separation.

87
00:09:34,981 --> 00:09:38,846
Every time I separate from something, I'm disidentifying.

88
00:09:39,653 --> 00:09:40,813
I'm relocating.

89
00:09:41,554 --> 00:09:43,177
I'm relocating where I think I am.

90
00:09:44,798 --> 00:09:52,547
So you've got to relocate out of the body, relocate out of the sensations, feelings, emotions, relocate out of thought.

91
00:09:54,489 --> 00:09:58,573
If I were going for this election next year, I'd be saying, relocate, relocate, relocate.

92
00:10:00,895 --> 00:10:08,985
So this constant relocation, I'm finding another place in which I can find, shall we say, a different identity.

93
00:10:10,062 --> 00:10:14,826
And this identity I experience as being the observer, the feeler.

94
00:10:15,346 --> 00:10:20,972
It's a very strange place to be because here I know what's happening.

95
00:10:21,913 --> 00:10:24,136
I feel an emotion.

96
00:10:24,197 --> 00:10:24,976
I can feel it.

97
00:10:25,017 --> 00:10:26,359
I can feel a sensation.

98
00:10:27,139 --> 00:10:27,799
I can know it.

99
00:10:28,660 --> 00:10:30,243
And yet somehow I'm not it.

100
00:10:32,125 --> 00:10:35,749
Now that's all the Buddha's pointing to when he's saying, not me, not mine.

101
00:10:35,769 --> 00:10:37,149
This is not me, not mine.

102
00:10:38,226 --> 00:10:46,375
and the fact that it arises and passes away is also pointing out it can't be me or mine because one minute it's here and then it's gone how could it be me?

103
00:10:46,716 --> 00:11:07,136
the idea of a me is something permanent, substantial something that doesn't change so the first position that we take in our meditation is that observer, that feeler we sort of lift ourselves out of the body-mind complex in order to discover this observation post

104
00:11:07,774 --> 00:11:18,471
All the noting we do, all the techniques that you come across in Vipassana, and the technique I myself am teaching is known as the Mahasi technique, but there are many others.

105
00:11:19,393 --> 00:11:29,648
And if you go into Zen, or you go to Dzogchen, the Tibetan tradition, all these techniques are always trying to get the meditator to find this position, that's all.

106
00:11:29,812 --> 00:11:32,777
And from this position, you can get this objectivity.

107
00:11:33,236 --> 00:11:44,691
And these three characteristics, we've mentioned the two at the moment, this idea of impermanence and the fact that it's not me, not mine, becomes more and more apparent the more you practice it.

108
00:11:46,854 --> 00:11:55,264
Now, even though we get to this position of the observer, the knower, that's not your final position because there's still something there that knows itself.

109
00:11:56,375 --> 00:12:03,123
Now, if I have a sense of presence, this is me, it's also an object, so I can't be that either.

110
00:12:04,345 --> 00:12:09,350
Everything that I'm aware of can't be the awareness that's aware of it.

111
00:12:11,613 --> 00:12:19,763
So even at that point, which we can get to by an act of will, we can put ourselves into the observation post, is not the end point.

112
00:12:20,764 --> 00:12:23,967
The end point is even when that sense of self disappears.

113
00:12:24,808 --> 00:12:43,965
And occasionally that may happen to you in little blitz and blobs when you fall into an absorption, an absorption state where there's a sense of loss of a self and yet when you come out of that state you know that there has been a process of knowing, a process of seeing, a process of experience.

114
00:12:45,514 --> 00:12:49,500
These I like to call little Nibbanic moments, right?

115
00:12:49,520 --> 00:12:55,109
Even whether they're actually Nibbanic or not, let's not get into that discussion.

116
00:12:55,149 --> 00:13:00,616
But they're Nibbanic moments in the sense that just for that one moment, we've lost the sense of self.

117
00:13:01,298 --> 00:13:04,442
Now, you might say to yourself, well, I do that when I watch a good film.

118
00:13:06,024 --> 00:13:07,346
When you sit and watch a good film, that's it, you're gone.

119
00:13:07,388 --> 00:13:09,691
You wake up two hours later and you say, that was a fantastic film.

120
00:13:10,993 --> 00:13:14,457
But you weren't aware of yourself watching the film while you were watching the film.

121
00:13:14,523 --> 00:13:15,565
There was a loss of self.

122
00:13:16,586 --> 00:13:24,698
But unfortunately, we enter into those absorptions with an intention which corrupts the actual process.

123
00:13:24,839 --> 00:13:28,485
And the intention is, I, me, I'm going to enjoy myself.

124
00:13:29,385 --> 00:13:33,312
And as soon as you do that, you form a relationship with films.

125
00:13:34,214 --> 00:13:38,100
The film now becomes something that your happiness is dependent on.

126
00:13:39,110 --> 00:13:50,292
So after you've seen one film, there comes, in not too long a space afterwards, a thirst, a craving, an addiction to get another DVD.

127
00:13:50,972 --> 00:13:51,173
See?

128
00:13:51,192 --> 00:13:52,777
Or else life becomes meaningless.

129
00:13:54,340 --> 00:13:56,123
This is what I found, innit?

130
00:13:58,346 --> 00:14:04,957
So it's a case of recognizing that we're talking about two different levels of consciousness.

131
00:14:05,357 --> 00:14:13,331
There's a level of knowing, a level of the way we relate to the world, which is seeking happiness in the world.

132
00:14:13,971 --> 00:14:19,681
Now, this is where we come to the other of the three characteristics, which the Buddha called dukkha.

133
00:14:19,701 --> 00:14:25,029
Dukkha translates as a hard place.

134
00:14:25,668 --> 00:14:31,398
So we're in a hard place and it's a hard place because we've made this wrong relationship.

135
00:14:32,038 --> 00:14:40,753
And this fundamental delusion that we suffer from expresses itself in a search for happiness in the sensual world.

136
00:14:41,214 --> 00:14:42,917
That's how it expresses itself.

137
00:14:42,897 --> 00:14:56,171
Having identified ourselves with the body, having identified ourselves with our emotional life and our thought life, we're now trying to make this inner environment the happiness that we seek.

138
00:14:56,751 --> 00:14:57,152
That's all.

139
00:14:58,352 --> 00:15:05,301
So when I'm feeling well, when I'm feeling really fit and I'm walking up a hill or something, then that's happiness.

140
00:15:05,701 --> 00:15:06,581
I've made it, finally.

141
00:15:07,062 --> 00:15:07,602
See?

142
00:15:07,623 --> 00:15:09,225
Then I get to the top of the hill...

143
00:15:10,066 --> 00:15:12,288
And I've got to come down, and it all dribbles away.

144
00:15:12,328 --> 00:15:15,413
The body feels weak and tired, and I've got to have my orange juice.

145
00:15:17,294 --> 00:15:19,999
Emotionally speaking, I can create a situation.

146
00:15:20,499 --> 00:15:25,004
See, I try and find the right sort of person who makes me happy, the right sort of situation.

147
00:15:25,325 --> 00:15:28,168
And I find myself in this beautiful emotional euphoria.

148
00:15:29,070 --> 00:15:32,254
Nature, sex, drugs, rock and roll, it's wonderful.

149
00:15:33,916 --> 00:15:38,402
But unfortunately, as soon as I've got it, this emotion corrupts it, disappears it.

150
00:15:38,517 --> 00:15:39,317
falls away from me.

151
00:15:40,639 --> 00:15:50,486
But I still think that as long as I can just get the right thing, right job, right relationship, right house, right car, I will be definitely perfectly happy.

152
00:15:50,506 --> 00:15:59,375
So this search for happiness in the world is producing that stress that we are suffering.

153
00:15:59,394 --> 00:16:07,782
Because we constantly want to be happy in a world which cannot deliver, if only because it passes away.

154
00:16:09,533 --> 00:16:14,041
Now, to let go of that is the process of renunciation.

155
00:16:14,140 --> 00:16:19,711
To begin to let go of that as a place to find happiness is the process of renunciation.

156
00:16:20,673 --> 00:16:25,841
Now, renunciation isn't self-mortification in the sense that we're not trying to beat ourselves up.

157
00:16:25,881 --> 00:16:27,245
For heaven's sake, we're suffering enough.

158
00:16:28,767 --> 00:16:34,157
What we're trying to do is to let go of our attachment to things.

159
00:16:34,340 --> 00:16:42,653
And we do that by, through this meditation, beginning to realize what desire is.

160
00:16:43,433 --> 00:16:47,320
So the Buddha's Four Noble Truths, he begins with a very simple statement.

161
00:16:47,721 --> 00:16:49,923
Life is dukkha, it's a hard place.

162
00:16:50,745 --> 00:16:55,933
And the reason it's a hard place, he says, is because of a certain type of desire.

163
00:16:56,875 --> 00:17:01,241
It's a desire based on seeking happiness in the sensual world.

164
00:17:02,250 --> 00:17:07,819
And then he says, if you can get rid of that, you will actually come to the end of this dukkha.

165
00:17:08,441 --> 00:17:21,761
You'll actually come to a position in yourself where there is no more unsatisfactoriness, no more suffering, and you live, in his words, in contented and with it happy.

166
00:17:22,618 --> 00:17:25,642
When somebody complains to him and says, look, this training is very difficult.

167
00:17:26,303 --> 00:17:30,326
He says, well, it is difficult, but then people achieve this wonderful state, nibbana.

168
00:17:30,346 --> 00:17:32,348
And the guy says, nibbana, so what?

169
00:17:33,550 --> 00:17:34,070
So he's very serious.

170
00:17:34,151 --> 00:17:38,536
When you get there, he says, you are contented and with it happy.

171
00:17:38,816 --> 00:17:39,797
He's describing himself.

172
00:17:41,058 --> 00:17:49,587
So remember that the enlightenment or the liberation is not a destruction of what we have, but a refinement of what we have.

173
00:17:50,075 --> 00:18:04,857
When the Buddha is finally liberated, he doesn't turn into this sort of amorphous blob, you know, sitting under a tree with enlightenment, sort of glowing, you know, but unable to speak, like he's lost in the Ibanic bliss forever.

174
00:18:06,200 --> 00:18:08,824
He gets up, he walks, he talks, he relates.

175
00:18:09,364 --> 00:18:15,053
And the Buddha heart is these illimitables, right, which we'll practice this afternoon.

176
00:18:15,336 --> 00:18:42,795
love compassion joy and peace that's his heart you see and his intellect what had been first what had been such a a barrier to actually seeing the things the way they are and that's why remember in our meditation we're constantly dragging ourselves down into the body to get back to basic experience away from conceptual thinking remember that concepts always hold our history

177
00:18:43,315 --> 00:18:48,660
So whenever we experience something, we're always dumping our history on what we're experiencing.

178
00:18:49,621 --> 00:18:54,665
So that's why whenever you eat an apple, it's always compared with the last apple or the apples you ate.

179
00:18:54,686 --> 00:18:57,368
And it's either rubbish or brilliant or whatever.

180
00:18:57,869 --> 00:18:59,991
But actually, the apple is just an apple.

181
00:19:00,271 --> 00:19:08,039
And to taste the apple, this apple, this apple that I'm tasting, in its individuality, I have to forget all history.

182
00:19:08,527 --> 00:19:12,973
And to do that, I place my attention just in the eating, just on the tongue.

183
00:19:13,714 --> 00:19:13,875
See?

184
00:19:14,615 --> 00:19:16,078
See?

185
00:19:16,098 --> 00:19:22,167
So now, this liberation, when it came, did not take away his intellect.

186
00:19:22,228 --> 00:19:24,932
He used his intellect to express the Dharma.

187
00:19:25,012 --> 00:19:26,375
to express his teaching.

188
00:19:26,395 --> 00:19:30,464
So everything that we're doing is not an annihilation of anything.

189
00:19:30,565 --> 00:19:36,237
In fact, he says the only things that are annihilated are greed, hatred, and this fundamental delusion.

190
00:19:37,019 --> 00:19:41,367
Everything is returned to us in a purified form.

191
00:19:42,664 --> 00:20:01,315
So this dukkha, this unhappiness, this unsatisfactoriness, meaninglessness that might come about our lives, is all about, is all resting on this delusion that somehow we can find the happiness in this human form.

192
00:20:01,836 --> 00:20:02,096
See?

193
00:20:02,596 --> 00:20:05,382
And we make the mistake of thinking we are human beings.

194
00:20:05,902 --> 00:20:15,195
But all we mean by human being is a conventional coming together of carrots and apples, isn't it?

195
00:20:15,256 --> 00:20:17,459
And then thoughts and images.

196
00:20:17,558 --> 00:20:21,184
When you get it all together and it's all working properly, we call that human being.

197
00:20:21,664 --> 00:20:23,488
But when you take it apart, what is there?

198
00:20:24,717 --> 00:20:29,786
But it's just a combination of objects, which the Buddha calls aggregates.

199
00:20:30,647 --> 00:20:44,633
He calls them the five aggregates, the physical aggregates, the perceptual aggregates, the feeling aggregates, all the aggregates that we call our emotions and thoughts, and these acts of cognition, these acts of consciousness.

200
00:20:46,215 --> 00:21:02,784
And our process is to begin to see that all that actually is, you know, it says in the scriptures, just bubbles in a stream, just like a flame which is constantly changing, just burning fuel, but in a constant process of change.

201
00:21:03,545 --> 00:21:09,996
But the flame looks one, it looks whole, it looks entire, but actually it's just made of a constant flow of energy.

202
00:21:10,481 --> 00:21:18,459
So these three characteristics are what it is we're trying to experience directly.

203
00:21:19,101 --> 00:21:26,938
And to directly experience these three characteristics is to liberate us from this essential delusion.

204
00:21:26,917 --> 00:21:34,729
Now, you might think, therefore, that having been liberated from that, you just end up in a sense of annihilation, like there's nothing left.

205
00:21:35,369 --> 00:21:40,238
But the Buddha points out, keeps stressing the fact, that he's not teaching annihilation.

206
00:21:40,258 --> 00:21:48,690
He's actually teaching that there is an experience which is beyond the phenomenal experience of ordinary daily life.

207
00:21:49,371 --> 00:21:53,517
And he points to that by calling himself the Tathagata.

208
00:21:53,497 --> 00:21:57,323
And the Tathagata translates best as the one who's transcended.

209
00:21:57,363 --> 00:21:59,747
The one who is transcended.

210
00:22:00,669 --> 00:22:07,640
So every time we move into the position of the observer within ourselves, we're transcending the body.

211
00:22:08,240 --> 00:22:09,824
We're transcending emotion.

212
00:22:10,124 --> 00:22:11,507
We're transcending thought.

213
00:22:11,527 --> 00:22:14,711
We're finding a very different position within ourselves.

214
00:22:15,619 --> 00:22:31,940
And when occasionally in your meditation there is that loss of self, there is that absorption into what we're observing, and with the loss of self you'll lose a sense of time, we're catching just moments of Nibbanic bliss.

215
00:22:32,820 --> 00:22:39,990
And the problem with that for us, because we associate bliss and happiness with emotions, is that there is no emotions there.

216
00:22:41,117 --> 00:22:50,384
So when Sariputta is asked, you talk about the bliss, the happiness of emotions, but there are no emotions in Nibbana.

217
00:22:50,423 --> 00:22:51,286
He says, yes, he says.

218
00:22:51,867 --> 00:22:55,096
It's the very absence of emotions which is the bliss in Nibbana.

219
00:22:55,116 --> 00:22:57,102
So there's a real conundrum for us.

220
00:22:57,924 --> 00:23:22,718
So, as in your meditation, when you can stabilize at some point this observer within you, when you can stabilize that position of just being within the phenomena of your own body, heart and mind, feelings, emotions, images, when you can stabilize that position long enough, for those of you who work at it,

221
00:23:23,676 --> 00:23:29,826
Ask yourself, what is the mood, the emotion, of the one who's observing?

222
00:23:32,229 --> 00:23:33,872
What is the mood of it, right?

223
00:23:34,152 --> 00:23:37,376
Just reflect on that for a moment.

224
00:23:37,396 --> 00:23:43,705
And that will draw you more and more to want to be in that place because that's where the peacefulness resides.

225
00:23:44,186 --> 00:23:48,553
It doesn't reside in the emotional life, it doesn't reside in the intellect or the body.

226
00:23:49,596 --> 00:23:55,545
Now, having done that, you might think to yourself, well, are you therefore denying the body, heart and mind?

227
00:23:55,605 --> 00:23:56,326
No, not at all.

228
00:23:56,807 --> 00:24:03,576
Because then, as it were, from that insight, you have to re-enter the whole psychophysical process.

229
00:24:04,377 --> 00:24:10,645
So the Buddha talks about right understanding, but then you have to draw yourself with right intention into the heart.

230
00:24:11,887 --> 00:24:18,237
And that right intention moves outwards into relationship, which is right speech, right action, right livelihood.

231
00:24:19,414 --> 00:24:41,625
and that mirrors back to you your wisdom or probably the lack of it and that's how you gain that's how you begin to understand that oh yes in sitting yes i consider those lovely and impermanent you know i never i can feel pain in my knee and i'm perfectly equanimous with that's absolutely wonderful you see and then you wait you're waiting for the tube and somebody stands on your foot

232
00:24:43,849 --> 00:24:45,673
To hell with meditation.

233
00:24:45,692 --> 00:24:55,226
So that's what we're trying to do in this, through the process of insight meditation, vipassana, right?

234
00:24:55,486 --> 00:24:59,251
We're trying to see these three characteristics more and more clearly.

235
00:24:59,592 --> 00:25:02,076
And it's in the seeing that the liberation comes.

236
00:25:03,096 --> 00:25:07,743
When you see something, then it rebounds back upon your attitude.

237
00:25:08,064 --> 00:25:11,769
You know, why do I want to keep, you know, doing this if it's making me unhappy?

238
00:25:12,150 --> 00:25:12,269
Right?

239
00:25:12,452 --> 00:25:13,215
It's very simple.

240
00:25:14,078 --> 00:25:16,268
So the seeing is the first point.

241
00:25:16,368 --> 00:25:18,678
It then moves, as I say, into right attitude.

242
00:25:18,738 --> 00:25:23,576
And this we develop through the practice of metta, loving-kindness.

243
00:25:25,345 --> 00:25:43,625
Now, those three characteristics, the characteristic of impermanence, the characteristic of how we create suffering for ourselves, the process, the role of sensual desire, and this teaching about not me, not mine, that's what we're trying to see.

244
00:25:44,424 --> 00:25:48,670
Now, what stops us seeing that are what the Buddha called these hindrances.

245
00:25:49,712 --> 00:25:52,656
And these hindrances you can split basically into two types.

246
00:25:53,479 --> 00:25:59,086
There's those types that excite the mind and keep it busy and take you away from this observing.

247
00:25:59,528 --> 00:26:02,653
And there's those types that drop you into the black hole.

248
00:26:03,453 --> 00:26:10,724
And dullness and lethargy, given a sort of moral twist by calling it sloth.

249
00:26:12,342 --> 00:26:39,867
and laziness and all that is there so as these mental states grab you right the meditator has to know well this is what it is and this is what I have to do to counteract it right and one thing that I think has been quite confusing to some people from some of the emails I get is that when something comes up

250
00:26:39,950 --> 00:27:09,230
which drags you away so for instance some planning you know you're planning a new business or something so you're planning to go on holiday and there's an excitement comes when you know planning planning you see right you come into the body this is why it's so important you come into the body and you get in contact with the excitement and you're allowing the excitement to express itself right express itself and to burn away

251
00:27:11,049 --> 00:27:22,161
When you have a depressive thought and you're feeling depressed and the mind goes off and off about, you know, the world's in a terrible state, we're all doomed, and I'm horrible, and all that sort of stuff.

252
00:27:22,181 --> 00:27:29,347
And you see, you come off the thought, you come into the body, and you contact the feeling of depression, and you go into it, you feel it.

253
00:27:30,548 --> 00:27:33,652
You're allowing the heart to express itself.

254
00:27:33,672 --> 00:27:39,538
If you find yourself arguing and you're getting very angry about something, you see, and you're strangling them,

255
00:27:40,025 --> 00:27:43,068
Then you say, oh, stop the anger, anger.

256
00:27:43,529 --> 00:27:44,691
You come back into the body.

257
00:27:46,053 --> 00:27:50,137
You find where, if you can, you can find where the anger is expressing itself.

258
00:27:50,578 --> 00:27:52,662
And you bury your attention into the heat.

259
00:27:54,483 --> 00:27:56,267
So you're not pushing anything away.

260
00:27:56,307 --> 00:27:59,631
You're not trying to run away from anything.

261
00:28:00,893 --> 00:28:04,917
Pushing away, running away are the usual way we suppress stuff.

262
00:28:05,201 --> 00:28:14,457
When something comes up we don't like, we either push it away with aversion, don't want to see it, or we run away from it, we turn away, we ignore it.

263
00:28:14,998 --> 00:28:17,923
All that produces psychological problems for us.

264
00:28:18,703 --> 00:28:19,625
Here we're not doing that.

265
00:28:19,685 --> 00:28:21,709
Here, when something comes up,

266
00:28:23,056 --> 00:28:30,186
We come off the mind and we bury ourselves in the emotional state and we give it the time to burn out.

267
00:28:31,209 --> 00:28:36,497
Some stuff takes a long time.

268
00:28:37,960 --> 00:28:44,349
You can expect to see true improvement over a period of something like 25 years.

269
00:28:45,070 --> 00:28:50,920
I don't want to give the impression that this happens overnight.

270
00:28:52,080 --> 00:29:02,417
What you're beginning to realize is that the emotional states that we've created have not been caused by the obvious object.

271
00:29:04,181 --> 00:29:10,089
So when somebody has annoyed us, when somebody has annoyed us, they've not caused the anger.

272
00:29:10,660 --> 00:29:11,760
It's really important.

273
00:29:12,402 --> 00:29:16,807
What's happened is we ourselves have come from a position of this.

274
00:29:17,568 --> 00:29:24,678
This person has disturbed this position and we've reacted from inside towards them with anger.

275
00:29:25,680 --> 00:29:26,861
The anger is caused by us.

276
00:29:28,462 --> 00:29:34,431
So therefore, seeking happiness by destroying the other is not going to help.

277
00:29:34,892 --> 00:29:38,717
You can annihilate everybody else in the world and you'll still end up angry and lonely.

278
00:29:39,718 --> 00:29:40,278
It doesn't...

279
00:29:41,541 --> 00:30:11,463
because they haven't actually caused the problem the problem lies within our own hearts which remember is always trying to seek happiness in the sensual world nobody has frightened us fear has arisen because of something in me has reacted to a situation nobody can cause us psychological pain

280
00:30:11,578 --> 00:30:14,624
It's all been caused inwardly by ourselves.

281
00:30:15,084 --> 00:30:18,990
It's really difficult, if you're new to this, to really sort of grasp that.

282
00:30:19,371 --> 00:30:21,594
And don't worry about it if you disagree.

283
00:30:23,958 --> 00:30:26,761
Nobody can cause a psychological pain.

284
00:30:26,781 --> 00:30:33,451
Now, the disappointment in that is that you can no longer blame somebody else.

285
00:30:33,803 --> 00:30:36,826
This is a real disappointment, because up until now it was great.

286
00:30:37,366 --> 00:30:40,670
Society, my parents, the dog, they were all to blame.

287
00:30:41,030 --> 00:30:42,432
But now, it's just you.

288
00:30:43,673 --> 00:30:51,461
But the liberation is that if I cause this, if I cause these awful mental states that I have to bear, I must be able to undo them.

289
00:30:52,803 --> 00:31:01,531
And that's where the liberation comes, that we are actually, we can become in charge of our own psychic life, our own psychological life.

290
00:31:02,895 --> 00:31:11,126
Now, the given, these hindrances when they come, so we've talked about the negative stuff, well, there's been a bit of excitement there.

291
00:31:11,146 --> 00:31:17,115
So there's excitement, there's depression, there's lust, there's romance, there's all the beautiful stuff too, I don't forget about that.

292
00:31:17,634 --> 00:31:21,560
And then there's all this other stuff, the anxiety, the depression, etc.

293
00:31:22,481 --> 00:31:25,885
All that, you see, has been caused by me.

294
00:31:27,208 --> 00:31:31,653
Now, what can I do about something which is already conditioned?

295
00:31:32,561 --> 00:31:37,866
If I try to destroy it, all I do is push it down.

296
00:31:37,906 --> 00:31:50,538
If I push it away like this and not want to see it, I know, we know from our own psychology, that it just makes more and more psychic problems for us.

297
00:31:51,358 --> 00:31:58,305
If I turn away from it, I know that it's just there within the psyche waiting for its little moment to appear.

298
00:31:59,546 --> 00:32:00,807
So what can I do?

299
00:32:01,847 --> 00:32:01,928
Hmm?

300
00:32:03,798 --> 00:32:06,023
The answer, of course, is to bear it.

301
00:32:06,766 --> 00:32:11,980
We have to suffer the consequences of our past unwholesome actions.

302
00:32:12,000 --> 00:32:14,949
And that's exactly what we're doing when we sit in meditation.

303
00:32:14,969 --> 00:32:17,978
We're allowing this stuff to arise and burn away.

304
00:32:19,020 --> 00:32:19,561
That's all.

305
00:32:20,892 --> 00:32:31,423
That's all we have to do, is to have the courage, the fortitude, the resilience to stay with the mental states and to allow them to rise and pass away.

306
00:32:31,844 --> 00:32:35,367
But to stay with them as felt sensations.

307
00:32:35,888 --> 00:32:50,865
As soon as they slip into the mind, as soon as we allow that moment of unmindfulness to come, and it slips into the mind as a dream, as a film, as a process, unwittingly we're developing the very same state.

308
00:32:51,384 --> 00:32:54,087
because that's how the emotions develop themselves.

309
00:32:54,107 --> 00:32:54,528
Consider.

310
00:32:55,209 --> 00:33:00,795
You know in the morning somebody said something a little bit off and you've just dismissed it.

311
00:33:01,935 --> 00:33:02,737
That's the way they are.

312
00:33:03,518 --> 00:33:07,903
And then tea time comes, eleven o'clock something, and you get a cup of tea.

313
00:33:07,982 --> 00:33:08,923
Bloody say that to me.

314
00:33:08,963 --> 00:33:12,748
And then at lunch it's raving.

315
00:33:13,409 --> 00:33:18,574
By the time you get home you don't want to see them in case you kill them.

316
00:33:19,481 --> 00:33:23,897
And all that's been created by us, by me.

317
00:33:23,958 --> 00:33:31,263
They only insulted me once, but I've had them insult me thousands of times before I go to bed.

318
00:33:31,970 --> 00:33:40,842
So, it's recognizing the role of the mind in developing our mental states that needs to be really perceived.

319
00:33:41,563 --> 00:33:49,554
And this business of, in meditation, of noting what's happening and coming back into the body, that's not just meditation.

320
00:33:49,574 --> 00:33:52,959
We have to do that throughout our lives, from the moment we wake up to the moment we fall asleep.

321
00:33:53,098 --> 00:34:01,790
Every time you see your mind wandering during the day, there has to be that effort to stop, note it, come into the body, allow the emotion to dissipate a bit.

322
00:34:05,804 --> 00:34:33,313
when it comes so all that really I'm describing here how to generally attack four of these hindrances those to do with happiness and pleasures and all that those to do with angers depressions all the negative stuff about life those to do with just general restlessness you know where the mind is just busy all the time or there's a feeling of restlessness in the body you know just to relax into it and feel it and just allow it to expend its energy and doubt

323
00:34:33,293 --> 00:34:36,257
Doubt here is skeptical doubt.

324
00:34:36,277 --> 00:34:38,579
The Buddha wants us to be in a state of wonder.

325
00:34:39,402 --> 00:34:45,190
He wants us to actually doubt his word in that very positive way of saying to ourselves, now, is this true or not?

326
00:34:45,369 --> 00:34:46,811
Because it's an investigation.

327
00:34:47,152 --> 00:34:49,416
It's the investigation that draws us to liberation.

328
00:34:49,956 --> 00:34:52,599
It's no good sort of believing in the Buddha and what he said.

329
00:34:52,639 --> 00:34:53,360
That's not going to

330
00:34:53,340 --> 00:34:55,266
I mean, it's not going to help at all.

331
00:34:55,648 --> 00:34:56,771
Faith is something different.

332
00:34:56,791 --> 00:34:57,755
It's confidence.

333
00:34:57,775 --> 00:35:05,038
And the confidence is there to make it easy for us to investigate the teachings.

334
00:35:06,840 --> 00:35:08,322
And skeptical doubt is something else.

335
00:35:08,342 --> 00:35:09,905
Skeptical doubt is always based on fear.

336
00:35:09,925 --> 00:35:11,266
It's fear of commitment, isn't it?

337
00:35:12,007 --> 00:35:13,170
An aversion to commitment.

338
00:35:13,190 --> 00:35:14,130
You don't want to go there.

339
00:35:14,512 --> 00:35:18,496
And when skeptical doubt enters into our ordinary lives, it can be absolutely crippling.

340
00:35:18,717 --> 00:35:22,461
Because you can't, is this the job I should be doing?

341
00:35:22,481 --> 00:35:22,902
Is it not?

342
00:35:22,922 --> 00:35:23,403
Should I do it?

343
00:35:23,423 --> 00:35:23,704
Should I not?

344
00:35:23,724 --> 00:35:24,344
And the job goes.

345
00:35:25,085 --> 00:35:26,307
Is this the person I really love?

346
00:35:26,327 --> 00:35:26,807
Should I love?

347
00:35:26,909 --> 00:35:27,489
Should I be married?

348
00:35:27,509 --> 00:35:27,969
Should I not?

349
00:35:27,989 --> 00:35:30,873
Before they've gone off, they've gone off to somebody else.

350
00:35:31,512 --> 00:35:35,197
So skeptical doubt is a real sort of undermining thing.

351
00:35:35,217 --> 00:35:40,525
And in your meditation, really, if that comes up, you know, everybody else can do it, I can't do it, I'm no good.

352
00:35:40,885 --> 00:35:50,077
Really come off the thought, come off the thought, go into the feeling of that doubt and let it express itself, the fear, whatever.

353
00:35:51,425 --> 00:35:55,012
The final one is the business of doneness and lethargy.

354
00:35:55,554 --> 00:35:56,597
And it's a big hindrance.

355
00:35:56,856 --> 00:36:00,364
I mean, you know, falling asleep in our meditation all the time.

356
00:36:00,385 --> 00:36:07,340
And of course, when you look back into the way we've used sleep to escape problems,

357
00:36:08,873 --> 00:36:13,539
You know, every time we feel a bit depressed, well, you just, you know, it's like head for the bed, you know.

358
00:36:15,842 --> 00:36:17,764
Big neon lights, head for the bed.

359
00:36:18,547 --> 00:36:22,692
Or you just lie down on the couch, you know, fed up, and off you go.

360
00:36:23,574 --> 00:36:23,994
Great, isn't it?

361
00:36:24,375 --> 00:36:26,617
I mean, oblivion, there's no suffering.

362
00:36:29,240 --> 00:36:31,724
And then you wake up, which is unfortunate.

363
00:36:32,246 --> 00:36:37,512
But if you would say completely oblivious, see, I mean, if death is complete annihilation, what's the problem?

364
00:36:42,708 --> 00:36:48,054
So unfortunately, we keep waking up out of this.

365
00:36:48,235 --> 00:36:53,461
But what we're doing is we're creating that inner habit of falling asleep.

366
00:36:53,481 --> 00:36:59,208
And it comes up as these feelings of heaviness, sloth, torpor, etc.

367
00:36:59,750 --> 00:37:06,858
And there's also, of course, the fact that being in that gentle subliminal state on a Sunday morning is really nice, isn't it?

368
00:37:07,378 --> 00:37:21,916
You know when you wake up and you turn over and you're just sort of wandering on that pleasant dreamy state or get back into bed and you just keep wandering on that lovely subliminal state of not being quite asleep and not being quite awake.

369
00:37:22,576 --> 00:37:28,123
And developing that is developing sloth and torpor, dullness and lethargy.

370
00:37:28,503 --> 00:37:32,728
So we shouldn't be surprised when we come to sit that we're always sort of bobbing up and down, falling asleep.

371
00:37:33,552 --> 00:37:44,914
So all these things that we're experiencing here in our meditation in terms of these negative mental states, we have to bring that practice into our daily life.

372
00:37:45,414 --> 00:37:49,563
Every time you feel sleepy during the day, ask yourself, now is this real tiredness?

373
00:37:50,264 --> 00:37:53,349
Or is it just this dullness and lethargy?

374
00:37:53,690 --> 00:37:55,914
In which case, stay awake.

375
00:37:56,722 --> 00:37:59,824
Every time you see your mind wandering, you have to note it and bring it back.

376
00:38:00,226 --> 00:38:05,371
So the practice of vipassana is something that we have to take into just every daily life.

377
00:38:06,512 --> 00:38:13,621
And remember that the thing that really helps the process, the spiritual process, is to relax.

378
00:38:15,021 --> 00:38:18,525
So if you find your life too busy, try and do something to make it less busy.

379
00:38:19,887 --> 00:38:26,695
Try to experience this standing meditation that we did in the morning as a constant throughout the day, every so often just to stop

380
00:38:27,568 --> 00:38:28,971
It's a really powerful word, you see.

381
00:38:29,411 --> 00:38:30,193
Just stop.

382
00:38:34,440 --> 00:38:34,679
Stop.

383
00:38:43,614 --> 00:38:45,117
I think I've stopped too.

384
00:38:46,759 --> 00:38:49,003
So,

385
00:38:49,978 --> 00:39:08,072
What we've described is these three characteristics which we're investigating, the sense of impermanence, the sense of not me, not mine, and the role of sensual desire, all based on some fundamental delusion within us that we're seeking happiness in the wrong place.

386
00:39:09,487 --> 00:39:12,653
And while we're doing that, these hindrances draw us away.

387
00:39:13,315 --> 00:39:22,273
Old habits of thought, old addictions, little hatreds, depressions, they're all drawing us away into this dream world.

388
00:39:22,996 --> 00:39:26,483
And all we have to do is to come off the dream

389
00:39:26,563 --> 00:39:33,213
re-establish that awareness within the body and let these things express themselves as feeling.

390
00:39:33,675 --> 00:39:34,996
That's all, as feeling.

391
00:39:35,737 --> 00:39:42,648
And when occasionally there does descend upon you some blissful peacefulness, see,

392
00:39:42,764 --> 00:39:46,547
Be careful you don't sink into that as you would ice cream.

393
00:39:47,789 --> 00:39:56,235
Try to still maintain the fact of observing it as something which is very pleasant, very beautiful, but also impermanent.

394
00:39:56,255 --> 00:39:59,119
Don't get drawn into beautiful states of mind.

395
00:39:59,878 --> 00:40:00,639
And use it.

396
00:40:00,739 --> 00:40:12,771
Those are really good moments to really draw the attention into the breath and begin to experience impermanence and to develop that sense of laser beam concentration.

397
00:40:12,751 --> 00:40:15,393
Laser beams, stillness and attention.

398
00:40:17,054 --> 00:40:22,699
And finally, just to bring an image to your mind of the child.

399
00:40:24,041 --> 00:40:32,889
So when somebody before the age of seven sees something they don't know, you see in a child, what do they do, you see?

400
00:40:33,230 --> 00:40:35,371
They become locked onto the object, don't they?

401
00:40:35,492 --> 00:40:37,873
Their eyes don't move.

402
00:40:37,893 --> 00:40:41,356
They're just locked onto the object, a beetle that they've never seen before.

403
00:40:42,434 --> 00:40:43,815
Everything goes absolutely still.

404
00:40:43,916 --> 00:40:45,016
The body relaxes.

405
00:40:45,418 --> 00:40:47,780
The jaw relaxes.

406
00:40:47,800 --> 00:40:48,762
They look gormless.

407
00:40:50,123 --> 00:40:54,170
And the good parent gives them a clip on the back of their head.

408
00:40:54,190 --> 00:40:55,030
They look gormless.

409
00:40:55,291 --> 00:40:57,954
The jaw's completely relaxed, which means there's no thought.

410
00:40:58,596 --> 00:41:04,923
That's why in your meditation, always make sure your jaw's relaxed, your tongue's relaxed.

411
00:41:04,943 --> 00:41:05,864
And they're just watching.

412
00:41:06,485 --> 00:41:10,871
And then after a moment or so, they stop and they ask, what is it?

413
00:41:12,184 --> 00:41:16,356
Now all that learning has gone on in just that watching.

414
00:41:16,456 --> 00:41:19,485
And all we're trying to do is get back to that state.

415
00:41:20,648 --> 00:41:23,175
Just that state of the original child.

416
00:41:23,556 --> 00:41:26,784
And that's why in Zen they'll often talk to you about original mind.

417
00:41:28,402 --> 00:41:50,889
So if you keep that image in your mind as a child, and that's what you're trying to get back to, a non-thinking state of pure observation, and having the trust, it really depends upon faith, having the trust that there is within us a superb intelligence which will see the way things are and liberate itself.

418
00:41:52,170 --> 00:41:57,496
That intelligence is constantly saying, get that meditator out of the way.

419
00:41:58,405 --> 00:42:04,297
Will that meditator please go home and just let me look?

420
00:42:04,496 --> 00:42:04,878
Okay?

421
00:42:05,338 --> 00:42:08,722
So that's your big problem, right?

422
00:42:08,762 --> 00:42:11,467
That's our big problem, is to get this meditator out of the way.

423
00:42:11,867 --> 00:42:13,989
And we do it in a very, very simple way.

424
00:42:14,550 --> 00:42:23,282
We just relax, we place the attention on the breath, we raise the interest to observe these three characteristics, and we just watch.

425
00:42:23,804 --> 00:42:24,664
We just feel.

426
00:42:25,025 --> 00:42:31,034
We just experience whatever draws the attention within the field of awareness.

427
00:42:33,817 --> 00:42:34,318
Voila.

428
00:42:37,824 --> 00:42:39,478
So, thank you very much.

429
00:42:39,940 --> 00:42:44,898
What we can do now is some walking meditation.

